<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="97" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="44" pageNumber="97">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="44" pageNumber="97">
The specific name, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="97">stevensoni</emphasis>
, proposed by Arnold (December, 1929) is pre-occupied by 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="97">stevensoni</emphasis>
Parker (June, 1929) and in consequence 
<bibRefCitation author="Arnold, G" journalOrPublisher="Occasional Papers of the National Museum of Southern Rhodesia" pageId="52" pageNumber="105" pagination="1 - 38" refId="B7" refString="Arnold, G, 1944. New species of African Hymenoptera. No. 5. Occasional Papers of the National Museum of Southern Rhodesia 2: 1 - 38" title="New species of African Hymenoptera. No. 5." volume="2" year="1944">Arnold (1944)</bibRefCitation>
proposed the substitute name 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="97">triangulifera</emphasis>
, at the same time describing the hitherto unknown female. However, both the holotype male and the allotype female are labelled in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Arnold’s">Arnold's</normalizedToken>
handwriting as 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="97">angulifera</emphasis>
, not 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="97">triangulifera</emphasis>
.
</paragraph>
